This is a test of the Observable Markdown (`.omd`) format. It combines regular markdown prose with executable JavaScript code blocks and inline expression interpolation.

### Interactive Input

```js
viewof radius = Inputs.range([0, 100], {
  step: 1,
  value: 50,
  label: "Radius"
})
```

The current radius is **${radius}**.

### Reactive Visualization

```js
htl.html`
  <svg width="220" height="220" viewBox="-10 -10 220 220">
    <circle cx="100" cy="100" r="${radius}" fill="transparent" stroke-width="2" stroke="currentColor" />
  </svg>
`
```

### `const` / `let` / `var` Cell Syntax

Observable Framework-style declaration keywords work the same as bare assignment:

```js echo
const greeting = "Hello from OMD!"
```

The greeting is: **${greeting}**.

### Data Visualization with Plot

```js
const data = [
  {category: "A", value: 28},
  {category: "B", value: 55},
  {category: "C", value: 43},
  {category: "D", value: 91},
  {category: "E", value: 81},
  {category: "F", value: 53}
]
```

```js
Plot.plot({
  marks: [
    Plot.barY(data, {x: "category", y: "value", fill: "steelblue"})
  ],
  width: 400,
  height: 300
})
```

### Standard Library

Standard library packages (`d3`, `Plot`, `Inputs`, `htl`, and others) are provided automatically by the Observable stdlib via lazy CDN loading. No import statements needed — just reference the package name in a cell:

```js echo
colorScale = d3.scaleSequential(d3.interpolateViridis).domain([0, 5])
```

```js
htl.html`<div style="display: flex; gap: 2px;">${
  d3.range(6).map(i => htl.html`<div style="width: 40px; height: 40px; background: ${colorScale(i)}; border-radius: 4px;"></div>`)
}</div>`
```

### Explicit Imports

You can import specific functions from npm packages using standard `import` syntax. Packages installed in `node_modules/` can be imported with a bare specifier; the `npm:` prefix fetches from esm.sh at build time (no local install needed).

```js
import { format } from "d3-format"
```

Formatted pi: **${format(".4f")(Math.PI)}**.

Imports can use `as` to rename:

```js
import { schemeTableau10 as tableau } from "npm:d3-scale-chromatic"
```

The first Tableau-10 color is **${tableau[0]}**.

### Multi-Statement Blocks

A single code block can contain multiple statements, including imports and declarations:

```js echo
import { precisionFixed } from "d3-format"
const piPrecision = precisionFixed(0.0001)
const doubled = Math.PI * 2
```

Pi precision: **${piPrecision}**, doubled: **${doubled}**.

### Loading Local Data

Data files stored alongside the `.omd` source can be loaded with `FileAttachment`:

```js
penguins = FileAttachment("penguins.csv").csv({typed: true})
```

```js
Plot.plot({
  marks: [
    Plot.dot(penguins, {x: "bill_length_mm", y: "bill_depth_mm", fill: "species", tip: true})
  ],
  color: {legend: true},
  width: 500,
  height: 300
})
```

There are **${penguins.length}** penguins in the dataset.

### Code Display (not executed)

Here's an example of syntax-highlighted code that is *not* executed:

```javascript
// This is just a code sample
const greeting = "hello world"
console.log(greeting)
```

### Echo Mode

This block is both displayed as source code and executed:

```js echo
areaOfCircle = Math.PI * radius ** 2
```

The area of the circle is **${areaOfCircle}** square pixels. It updates reactively when the radius slider changes.
